{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778560554,"nonce":"x3vTt7wgHDStbYfksewvFOb80EI=","title":"Tier 1: GRU affine decomposition + bimodality clustering on existing models","message":"Part of phase umbrella `f695729`. Follow-up from the `d448c9d` consultation synthesis (2026-05-11) — Tier 1 of the recommended path.\n\n## Motivation\n\nBoth external reviewers (Gemini 3.1 Pro, GPT-5.5 via codex) independently recommended this as the highest-leverage step: it requires zero new training and directly tests whether the GRU empirically *does* what the decoupling hypothesis says it does — separates feedforward (nominal motion) from feedback (deviation correction) — without committing to any new architecture-engineering MVP.\n\n## Sub-items\n\n### 1.1 GRU affine decomposition\n\nTake baseline GRU and adversarially-trained GRU (existing flavor-B models from synthesis.md §5.3 / `c723082`). For each, on a clean undisturbed reach:\n\n- Extract the nominal trajectory `x_nom(t)` and nominal control sequence `u_0(t)` from a rollout\n- Linearize the GRU output at every timestep around `x_nom(t)`: compute `K_local(t) = -∂u/∂x_feedback` along the trajectory via Jacobian\n- Compute the residual nonlinearity: error of local affine reconstruction `u(t, x) ≈ u_0(t) - K_local(t)·(x - x_nom(t))` under small perturbations\n- Report the nominal/feedback power split: `||u_0||²` vs `||K_local · e||²`\n\nVerify whether `src/rlrmp/analysis/induced_gain.py` already provides this machinery; if not, extend it. Compare baseline vs adversarial GRU on all four quantities.\n\n**Decision criterion**: if `||K_local_adv|| \u003e\u003e ||K_local_base||` while `u_0_adv ≈ u_0_base` and the residual nonlinearity stays small, the GRU is empirically acting as a tracker and the decoupling hypothesis is confirmed at the representational level. If the residual is large, the affine-tracker interpretation fails and we need a richer functional decomposition.\n\n### 1.2 Bimodality clustering on flavor-B replicates\n\nThe flavor-B Δv distribution is bimodal: ~25% of replicates at +40 to +57%, the rest at -20 to -26%. Averaging across seeds is hiding the mechanism. Cluster the existing replicates by:\n\n- Nominal velocity profile (full trajectory, not just peak)\n- Final training loss\n- Final adversarial loss\n- Local feedback Jacobian norm (from 1.1)\n- Hidden-state trajectory PCA (low-rank structure)\n- Readout norm\n- Pre-go drift / hold drift\n\n**Decision criterion**: if positive-Δv replicates structurally differ from negative-Δv replicates on multiple of these features, treat them as two distinct basins (e.g. H∞-like vs slow-conservative). Report the clean per-basin Δv signatures separately, not the average.\n\n## Dependencies / prerequisites\n\nNone — uses existing trained models. Should be doable in a single laptop-CPU session.\n\n## Cross-refs\n\n- Parent: `d448c9d` (decoupling acid test)\n- Umbrella: `f695729` (regulator-coupling phase)\n- Consultation: `results/d448c9d/consultations/2026-05-11_decoupling_framing/`\n- Related: `c723082` (LinearDynamicsAdversary / flavor-B trained models)\n- Analyses coord: `4d38c15` (this is a new analysis worth doing)","files":null}]}